				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${^{\,8}\text {Be}^{*}(17.64)} \rightarrow {^{\,8}\text {Be}}+a(17)$$\end{document},22ΓaΓγ|8Be∗(17.64)≈(0.08-10)×10-7.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \frac{\varGamma _a}{\varGamma _\gamma }\;\Bigg |_{^8\text {Be}^*(17.64)}\approx (0.08-10)\times 10^{-7}. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}We infer from (22) that the a(17) hypothesis provides a natural explanation for the absence of a statistically significant excess in this transition (at least with the integrated proton beam luminosity of public results to date).

Finally, we re-iterate that because the axion is a pseudoscalar, it can only be produced in magnetic multipole emissions. Hence, unlike the protophobic X17 vector boson case, the rate for the non-resonant capture reaction p+7Li→8Be+a(17)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
